  :prose
"The two-body problem is solved. Kepler and Newton did it. Given a
planet and a sun, we can write down where the planet will be at any
future time using conic sections — ellipses, parabolas, hyperbolas.
The math is beautiful and the answer is exact.

The three-body problem is not solved. There is no general closed-form
solution. There are special solutions — Lagrange points, figure-eight
orbits — but for a generic three-body system the only way to know
where the bodies will be in a year is to simulate them, step by step,
and even then rounding errors accumulate. This is a startling gap in
our understanding of the universe. And it is exactly the point where
'physics is the game' becomes 'physics is the surprise.'

This chapter builds a two-body orbit that returns to its starting
position, a three-body system that sometimes stays and sometimes flies
apart, and an eight-body toy solar system you can perturb. Along the
way we introduce `topo/knot` to detect knotted orbits and
`topo/writhe` to measure how tangled they are.

---

## 4.1 The two-body orbit

```scheme
(define (two-body-orbit)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0)               ;; no external gravity
  (let ((sun    (world/spawn 'sun    240 180))
        (planet (world/spawn 'planet 340 180)))
    (entity/mass!    sun    100000)
    (entity/mass!    planet 100)
    (entity/pin!     sun)             ;; treat sun as fixed
    (entity/set-vel! planet 0 1.6)    ;; tangential velocity
    (world/attract!  planet sun 1.0)  ;; planet feels sun's pull
    (list sun planet)))

(two-body-orbit)
(on-frame
  (lambda (t)
    (world/step)
    (let ((p (entity/pos (world/find 'planet)))
          (s (entity/pos (world/find 'sun))))
      (paint-circle (car s) (cdr s) 6 yellow)
      (paint-circle (car p) (cdr p) 3 white))))
```

Pin the sun so it doesn't drift. Give the planet a tangential
velocity. It orbits. Try different velocities: too slow, it spirals
in; too fast, it escapes on a hyperbola. In between, ellipses. There
is a magic velocity — `v = sqrt(G*M/r)` — that gives a perfect
circle. Below that, ellipse tilting inward; above, ellipse tilting
outward. This is one of those places where a formula and a running
simulation teach the same thing at once.

## 4.2 Trace the orbit as a curve

Every N frames, save the planet's position. Reconstruct the orbit as
a Bezier or Catmull-Rom curve for a smooth trail.

```scheme
(define trail '())

(on-frame
  (lambda (t)
    (world/step)
    (let ((p (entity/pos (world/find 'planet))))
      (when (= 0 (modulo t 3))
        (set! trail (cons p trail))
        (when (> (length trail) 200)
          (set! trail (take trail 200))))
      ;; Draw the trail as a smooth curve.
      (let ((curve (curve/catmull-rom trail)))
        (curve/paint! curve 1 green)))))
```

The trail closes on itself if you have a bound orbit. For a bound
orbit, it eventually completes and the ellipse begins to overwrite
itself perfectly — every point on the ellipse is on top of every
previous point. That is Kepler.

## 4.3 The three-body: add a moon

```scheme
(define (three-body)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((sun    (world/spawn 'sun    240 180))
        (planet (world/spawn 'planet 340 180))
        (moon   (world/spawn 'moon   358 180)))
    (entity/mass!    sun    100000)
    (entity/mass!    planet 100)
    (entity/mass!    moon   1)
    (entity/pin!     sun)
    (entity/set-vel! planet 0 1.6)
    (entity/set-vel! moon   0 2.2)
    (world/attract!  planet sun    1.0)
    (world/attract!  moon   sun    1.0)
    (world/attract!  moon   planet 1.0)
    (world/attract!  planet moon   1.0)))

(three-body)
```

Sometimes the moon stays. Sometimes it gets slingshot away on a
hyperbola after a close encounter. Sometimes the planet's orbit is
perturbed just enough that everything gradually drifts. The outcome
depends acutely on the moon's initial velocity — change 2.2 to 2.1
and the moon stays for hundreds of orbits; change it to 2.4 and it
escapes on the first pass.

This is the difference between two-body and three-body. Two-body has
answers. Three-body has behaviors.

## 4.4 Detecting knots in orbits

If we sample the moon's trajectory and connect the samples, we get a
closed curve in space (or in the plane, for our 2D sim). Is this
curve knotted? For 2D it can't be — real knots live in 3D — but the
`topo/knot` verb also gives us WRITHE, which measures how tangled a
2D curve is with itself.

```scheme
(define (writhe-of-moon-orbit T)
  (world/reset!)
  (three-body)
  (let loop ((n T) (pts '()))
    (if (<= n 0)
        (let ((curve (reverse pts)))
          (topo/writhe curve))
        (begin
          (world/step)
          (let ((p (entity/pos (world/find 'moon))))
            (loop (- n 1) (cons p pts)))))))

(writhe-of-moon-orbit 2000)
;; => a real number. Higher = more self-crossings.
```

Simple orbits: writhe near zero. Moon-loops-around-planet-while-planet-
orbits-sun: writhe grows steadily. Escape trajectory: writhe stops
growing at the moment of escape. This is a topological signature of
what the sim is doing.

## 4.5 An eight-planet toy solar system

`phys/nbody` handles the boilerplate.

```scheme
(define (toy-solar)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((sun (world/spawn 'sun 240 180)))
    (entity/mass! sun 100000)
    (entity/pin!  sun)
    (let loop ((i 1) (planets '()))
      (if (> i 8)
          planets
          (let* ((r  (+ 40 (* i 22)))
                 (p  (world/spawn (string->symbol
                                    (string-append \"planet-\" (number->string i)))
                                  (+ 240 r) 180))
                 (v  (sqrt (/ 1.0 r))))    ;; circular-orbit velocity
            (entity/mass!    p (+ 10 (* i 5)))
            (entity/set-vel! p 0 v)
            (world/attract!  p sun 1.0)
            (loop (+ i 1) (cons p planets)))))))

(toy-solar)
```

Eight planets, near-circular orbits, no mutual gravity (yet). Add
mutual attractions and watch the outer planets slowly perturb the
inner ones. This is how real solar-system simulations work — the
'unperturbed' motion is Keplerian around the sun, and the mutual
attractions are treated as small corrections that accumulate.

Appendix I has realistic masses and distances for our own solar
system, in units suitable for `phys/nbody`.

---

## 4.6 The four routing patterns in orbital sim

**Composition.** `three-body` composes four `world/attract!` calls;
`toy-solar` composes eight (or twenty-eight with mutual). We can
compose 'add a Trojan asteroid at Sun-Jupiter L4' as a small extra
function.

**Orchestration.** The trail update, the writhe computation each 2000
frames, the tape record for later reproducibility — this is
orchestration across time.

**In-routing.** When two planets collide (rare but possible), the
engine routes to a collision handler that either merges them
(`world/on-collision! 'planet 'planet ...`) or just marks the event.

**Routing.** The orbit trail routes to a Bezier renderer. The writhe
value routes to a plot. The 'moon escaped at frame 1234' event routes
to Cortex: 'in scenario three-body-A, moon escapes when initial
velocity > 2.3.' That kind of memory is exactly what makes the runtime
useful — she can tell an operator 'last time you tried this
configuration it escaped after 15 orbits.'

---

## 4.7 Common desktop tasks

An estate-sale operator asked: 'we have a heavy chandelier and a
side-table clock swinging near each other. Can the vibrations from
the clock disturb the chandelier?' A two-body coupled-oscillator sim
answers this. Set the two masses, link them very weakly (they're
coupled via floor vibration), start one swinging, watch the other
pick up amplitude. This is not exactly the three-body problem, but
it's the same coupling story.

## 4.8 Try this

1. Change the planet's initial velocity by 0.01 each run. Where does
   the orbit type change from ellipse to escape?
2. Add a second planet with different mass. Do their orbits interfere?
3. Move the sun off-pin (`(entity/unpin! sun)`, `(entity/mass! sun 10)`).
   Does the sun start moving? Where does the center of mass end up?
4. Start the moon with velocity 0 (relative to planet). Does it fall
   into the planet?
5. Feed the moon's trajectory to `topo/persistence` (from chapter 13).
   Do stable orbits and escape trajectories have different topological
   signatures?

## 4.9 Pitfalls

**Energy drift.** Long simulations of orbits with plain Euler slowly
gain energy. Verlet or RK4 is much better. See Appendix A.

**Close encounters.** When two bodies pass VERY close, the force spike
can send one flying at speed-of-light-relative velocities. Use
`entity/max-speed!` or a softened potential (`world/attract!` with an
epsilon distance) to avoid.

**Pinning distortion.** Pinning the sun is a simplification — really,
the sun would move a bit in response to planets. For most solar-system
sims this is fine; for a two-body-of-equal-mass system it's wrong.

